<strong><font color = "#C00000"Size 5>COLLEGE RECRUITING and THE AAU BASKETBALL PROGRAM REVIEW</strong></font></p>

<p>In Following our column started last week, we have two additional athletes to be added to our list of student- athletes that are moving from high school to higher education by using sports as the tool to help pay for their education. This week the Maine Hoops Club, Mr. Tom Nolette, provides our list. </p>

<p>Chris Markwood, 6’4”, South Portland, Maine – Chris will be heading to Notre Dame on a full basketball scholarship (Division I school)</br>

<br>Ben Smith, 6’4”, Boothbay, Maine – Ben will be attending St. Michaels, Vermont, on a full basketball scholorship (Division  II school)</p>

<p>These two athletes help to speak the message that AAU and President Bobby Dodd have been preaching to anyone that would listen. He has addressed the National Federation of High Schools, the NCAA, and other organizations to attempt to defuse the argument from those parties that AAU coaches and other programs are money grabbing, headhunting, coattail riding agents that destroy young people by driving them hard during the summer. In reality, it is because of the good, well meaning individuals that give of their time and effort, for the athletes to participate in the off season, that athletes such as Ben Smith get a chance to get an college education by playing ball at a less than recognized school versus the Dukes, UNC’s, U.of Kentuckys, and other well known Division I schools. </p>

<p>Coach Bruce Howard who participates in the AAU program coaching the 15:U AAU All-Ohio Red. He defends playing summer basketball because it helps athletes get full rides  when they may otherwise slipped through the cracks. </p>

<p>“Don’t penalize the kids or the mid-major schools like the Daytons and the Xaviers and the Division II’s” Howard states. “The top schools are always going to get theirs, but what about the other kids?”</p>

<p>Recently, there was an article that was picked up by the Associated Press and other news media that referenced a situation where a coach, in the Chicago, Illinois area was disciplined by the AAU Boys’ Basketball Committee for allowing a young lady to play in an AAU tournament for boys. Many people thought the AAU was discriminating against young athletes but the AAU did nothing more than exercise its policies. The AAU has a program for female basketball players; in fact the AAU Girls’ Basketball program is the largest in the AAU’s stable of 32 sports. </p>

<p>If we stop and look at the AAU program, in overall prospective, we would realize that the AAU, through its 32 sport programs, carries the AAU slogan of Sports For All, Forever!, to the letter. The AAU sports programs are not just for super stars, as with some camps and apparel programs, but for the athletes. Athletes are given the same consideration when a college or university coach has the ability to attend a summer AAU tournament and see 1,000 or more athletes versus trying to visit a high school in between his own schedule or attending an elite event sponsored by a camp promoter. Many times the camp is held on a college or university campus. How convenient for that coach who is trying to recruit the best athletes.  </p>

<p>One of these days, the ‘ownership theory’ will leave us and the true meaning of “we are doing it for the kids” will come forth. Whether an athlete goes to a Division I school, Division II, Division III, NAIA, Junior College, Community College, or Technical School, lets encourage them to JUST GO. If by playing basketball or any sport can help them get an education, then we should encourage it. It sure does help the parent’s pocketbook. </p>

<p><strong><font color = "#C00000"Size 5>NCAA WOMEN SHOWCASE TALENT AT DISNEY'S WWS</strong></font></p>

<p>Sunday, December 5, 1999, the Walt Disney World Sports Complex was full of basketball talent that resembled and all star showcase. Involved in the single day affair were for of the top 10 teams in the NCAA rankings. The U. of Conn., number one in the country played Penn State, number 11. In the second game UCLA, number five, played Louisiana Tech, number four.</p>    
 
<p>Although both games were less than close, UCONN and LA TECH showed the viewing audience that they more than likely will be at the final four contested in March of 2000.  All four teams showcased young ladies that had participated in the AAU during their earlier years. The playmaker, passer, rebounder, and shooter, when needed for Conn., Shea Ralph, started in AAU Basketball events at the age of nine. She credits her AAU play for her ability to face the tough competition she faces now. From LA Tech, Tamicha Jackson, 5&#8217;5&#8221; Sr. from Dallas Texas, was seen on the court, but as a blur. She is an all-round good player, fast, a good shooter, rebounder,, and leader on the court. Penn State has a young ball team, but many of their athletes are adjusting in fine fashion due to their AAU experiences. </p>

<P>The AAU would like to thank INTERSPORT, and particularly Jacqui Weber, as the Florida AAU under the guidance of Mar Rodriguez worked with Ms. Weber and distributed over 1,000 tickets  to Florida AAU athletes and their families. Plans are already underway for the event next year.</p>    

