<br>Dear Paul:
 
<p>As a coach for the Savannah Silver Cheetahs Track & Field Club, the Games are a thrill for me. I ran AAU back in the 70's for Ambler Olympic Club, and Larry Wilson (chair for AAU X-C) was my coach throughout my entire youth. Now, I coach an AAU member club and every Games (either cross country or track/field) I get to see all those teams & coaches who are still around. Amazingly, I have bumped into old team mates and runners who I used to compete against. This is truly the long lived spirit of AAU. I cannot express how wonderful it is to see many years later those former AAU runners and talk about "those days" and who is doing what these days. It's also such a joy to see Mr. Wilson at least twice a year at Nationals. Coaches cannot know the impact they have on a young person's life until years later. Thanks AAU for all the fond memories (all of which are captured in my scrapbook, still have every race number ever worn, photos, AAU certificates, ribbons, you name it...I still have it). Thanks AAU for keeping quality people who encourage youth to excel. Thanks AAU for being a huge part of my life and I feel committed to give through coaching an AAU member club.</p>
 
  <br>Sincerely,
  <br>Maggie Keenan
  <br>"coach maggie" or "doc"
  <br>email: <A
HREF="MAILTO:doctormaggie@yahoo.com">doctormaggie@yahoo.com </A>

<p>What a wonderful testimony of an athlete turned volunteer. If Maggie Keenan has had a part in your life as a participant or as a friend, email her a message.</p> 







